Supporting Functions¶

In [2]:
def score_model(model, x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test):
        ## Score for training data set
        y_pred_train = model.predict(x_train)

        print(f"#### {type(model).__name__} - Training dataset scores ####")
        try:
            print(f"The intercept for model is {model.intercept_:.4f}")
        except:
            pass
        print(f'Mean Absolute Error: {mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_pred_train):.6f}')  
        print(f'Mean Squared Error: {mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred_train):.6f}')  
        print(f'Root Mean Squared Error: {np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred_train)):.6f}')
        print(f'R2 score: {model.score(x_train, y_train):.6f}')
        print()

        ## Score for testing data set
        y_pred_test = model.predict(x_test)

        print(f"#### {type(model).__name__} - Testing dataset scores ####")
        try:
            print(f"The intercept for model is {model.intercept_:.4f}")
        except:
            pass
        print(f'Mean Absolute Error: {mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred_test):.6f}')  
        print(f'Mean Squared Error: {mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_test):.6f}')  
        print(f'Root Mean Squared Error: {np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_test)):.6f}')
        print(f'R2 score: {model.score(x_test, y_test):.6f}')

This dataset is complete with 1599 non-null entries. I will be using it to see how well we can predict the amount of residual sugar in the wine, using the other columns as features. This is purely anecdotal, but for myself and most of my friends, how sweet a wine is determines whether we will like it much or not. This is pretty hard to gauge unless we taste the wine, or unless it is labelled sec, demi-sec, dry, brut, etc. The former requires money and potentially getting wine we don't find tasty. Labels are rare from my experience as well, most bottles simply state the type of wine.

I am hoping that there is a correlation between the features and sugar content, especially alcohol v. residual sugar. Alcohol content is always on the bottle, and if it can help predict residual sugar then we have a much better basis for choosing wine to try. We can also look at acidity, most stores we buy from mention this too, and it can usually be found on Google.

Image from https://winefolly.com/deep-dive/what-is-residual-sugar-in-wine/, which also has an explanation for residual sugar.

Model Training - Regression¶

Looking at the residual sugar column, nothing looks too strongly correlated. Nevertheless, we will train our models and see how accurate of a prediction we can make.

In [16]:
# Splitting into features and label

X = data.drop("residual sugar", axis=1).copy()
y = data["residual sugar"].copy()
In [17]:
# Creating a train/test split. I will reserve 20% of the data for testing.

x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.20, random_state=42)

model = linear_model.Lasso(alpha=0.1)
model.fit(x_train, y_train)

score_model(model, x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test)

#### Lasso - Training dataset scores ####

R2 score: 0.058361

#### Lasso - Testing dataset scores ####
The intercept for model is 1.2435
Mean Absolute Error: 0.685623
Mean Squared Error: 1.311199
Root Mean Squared Error: 1.145076
R2 score: 0.046882

Lasso Regression results are pretty abysmal. We won't be predicting anything based on these results.

In [18]:
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.20, random_state=42)

model = RandomForestRegressor(max_depth=10, random_state=0, n_jobs=-1, n_estimators=500)
model.fit(x_train, y_train)

score_model(model, x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test)

#### RandomForestRegressor - Training dataset scores ####
Mean Absolute Error: 0.318146
Mean Squared Error: 0.237636
Root Mean Squared Error: 0.487479
R2 score: 0.886205

#### RandomForestRegressor - Testing dataset scores ####
Mean Absolute Error: 0.482863
Mean Squared Error: 0.714764
Root Mean Squared Error: 0.845437
R2 score: 0.480434

The more powerful random forest regressor does much better in the training, but still has only about 50% accuracy with the test set. Perhaps it is a better idea to assert we will like wines with residual sugar greater than a certain threshold. We can then feed these features into a classifier, which will take into account how all the variables affect this preference. This may reveal other hidden trends I didn't consider previously.

Model Training - Classification¶

In [19]:
# Because this dataset is from a limited selection and type of wine, the residual sugar
# doesn't go higher than 15 g/L. Most dessert wines are around 45 g/L, while I personally
# consider >30 g/L sweet. For this case study, I will set values above 4 g/L as "tasty".

data['tasty'] = np.where(data['residual sugar'] >= 4, 1, 0)
In [20]:
# I will be using the LogisticRegressor. We need to normalize the data for this to work.
# 
# Splitting into features and label again, this time dropping residual sugar to not
# make the algorithm hyper-fixate on that variable (as there is technically a trivial 
# correlation between 'taste' and 'residual sugar' when the latter is > 4 g/L.

X = data.drop("tasty", axis=1).copy()
X = X.drop("residual sugar", axis=1)
X = StandardScaler().fit_transform(X)

y = data["tasty"].copy()
In [21]:
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.20, random_state=42)

model = LogisticRegression(random_state=42)
model.fit(x_train, y_train)

score_model(model, x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test)

#### LogisticRegression - Training dataset scores ####
Mean Absolute Error: 0.066562
Mean Squared Error: 0.066562
Root Mean Squared Error: 0.257997
R2 score: 0.933438

#### LogisticRegression - Testing dataset scores ####
Mean Absolute Error: 0.046875
Mean Squared Error: 0.046875
Root Mean Squared Error: 0.216506
R2 score: 0.953125

Let's create a confusion matrix and see where the model is making mistakes.

In [22]:
# Creating a CV scoring to get a more representative accuracy score
fold = KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=1, shuffle=True)
scores = cross_val_score(model, X, y, scoring='accuracy', cv=fold, n_jobs=-1)

cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, model.predict(x_test))

plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt=".3f", linewidths=.5, square = True, cmap='coolwarm');
plt.ylabel('Actual');
plt.xlabel('Predicted');
title = f'Accuracy: {np.mean(scores)*100:.2f}%'
plt.title(title, size = 15);

The model is mostly making false negative errors - saying I might not like a wine, but in actuality there's a high chance I would. Because there is so much wine out there to try I'm actually OK with this. In this case I prefer to miss a wine I might like since there are other channels where I might find out about it. I would not want to get a wine and be excited about it, only to find it unpleasant.

Conclusion¶

Even with the residual sugar variable not in the dataset anymore, the Logistic Regressor is still able to classify with very high accuracy whether I might consider a wine tasty or not.

My main requirement is the sugar content; I am open to try the various other combinations of features and check what I might enjoy. As long as the sweetness is there, I can minimize the effects of the other predictors on my palate. The results are more valuable that I originally thought! This would allow me to broaden my tastes in a much more structured manner than just buying random bottles of wine.

Further Improvements¶

The dataset is limited as discussed above, and also missing some features I think would be helpful in classification. Below I outline some improvements to the data I think would help.

  • Include wine_color as a feature, determining if it is red, white, etc.
  • Include more types of wine; dessert, champagne, ros.
  • Include wines from regions other than Portugal.
  • Include more data points!
